<TEXT>
kuwaiti soldiers in tanks roar 
through blowing desert sand for the cameras kuwaiti volunteers 
practice lethal karate chops in front of photographers kuwaiti 
refugees tell reporters the horrors of life under the iraqis 
its all part of a steppedup media campaign by the exiled 
kuwaiti government to keep the plight of kuwait on newscasts and 
front pages around the world 
i want this issue always to be in the minds of people because 
as time passes people may forget said amal alhamad who was in 
charge of international media in kuwaits ministry of information 
and is now running an information office at a dhahran hotel 
nearly four months after the iraqi invasion of their country 
and with a growing antiwar movement in the united states the 
kuwaiti government has zeroed in on the hundreds of media 
representatives here covering the us military buildup and allied 
deployment 
in the three weeks since her office opened for business 
scarcely a day has passed without a kuwaiti event all orchestrated 
with the help of the rendon group a washington public relations 
firm 
what we try to do is to give the media a clear picture of 
what the iraqis are doing we are trying to make the world 
sympathize with us sympathize with the truth she said 
trips to see the remnants of the kuwaiti army talk to kuwaiti 
pilots who flew here after the invasion and watch kuwaiti 
volunteers train are especially popular 
the ministry of information has also brought government 
officials from their exile headquarters in taif and keeps two 
people at the border looking for fleeing refugees who can provide 
insight into the situation inside kuwait 
the refugees are then brought here to recount their tales of 
iraqi repression corruption and murder 
some like dr ali alhuwail go on the record and make 
headlines he told of burying more than 50 kuwaiti children in one 
night with a colleague who witnessed the iraqis pulling the plugs 
on some of their incubators 
others cover their faces and refuse to give their names because 
they are frightened of what might happen to family members left 
behind 
mrs alhamad who left kuwait with her family in early october 
said she recognizes that not everyone produces a story some may 
only provide a few facts but each adds a piece to the picture 
the kuwaiti operation has not always run smoothly often because 
of poor logistics 
the kuwaiti government was late in starting a public relations 
operation partly because many employees from the ministry of 
information are still in kuwait and all its archives were stolen 
mrs alhamad said 
it now has an office in cairo and is planning new operations in 
london syria northern africa and other european countries she 
said 
money is no problem mrs alhamad said though she had no 
overall figure on the cost of the international media campaign 
the rendon group was hired because it knew what the western 
media needed she said 
john rendon the firms president said in a telephone interview 
that his company was mainly providing technical assistance in saudi 
arabia europe and arab capitals to help the kuwaitis get their 
message across 
the first public relations campaign on behalf of kuwait was 
launched in the united states in midaugust by hill and knowlton 
it was hired by citizens for a free kuwait formed by private 
kuwaiti citizens immediately after the aug 2 iraqi invasion 
lew allison hill and knowltons senior vice president who 
arrived in saudi arabia on aug 22 said his main job has been to 
produce tv news of kuwaitis and transmit it back to washington he 
said he had worked closely with the kuwaiti government especially 
when it had no public relations operation here 
al mattern 40 of alexandria va who started up rendons 
saudi operation said he felt he was doing something worthwhile 
for mankind rather than just raise money for political candidates 
at home 
mrs alhamad said the kuwaitis who staff an office here are all 
unpaid volunteers like herself though some are getting living 
expenses 
we are ready to sacrifice she said even if i succeed in 
only 3 percent of what i expect i think i have done something for 
my country 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

