<DOCNO> AP901123-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
hosni mubarak egypts prudent president 
took an uncharacteristic political gamble in leading arab 
opposition to iraqs saddam hussein 
that gamble appears to be paying off experts say as mubarak 
hosted bush for a 19hour visit starting thanksgiving night 
iraq invaded kuwait on aug 2 and ignited the crisis that has 
close to threequarters of a million soldiers iraqi vs us and 
its allies ready for battle on the saudi peninsula 
until the invasion mubaraks leadership style was cautious and 
hesitant many said plodding but he had laboriously ended a 
decades isolation from the arabs and was trying to cement cairos 
position as the natural arab leader when saddam undercut him 
mubarak 62 and president for nine years moved quickly to 
marshal arab forces against iraqs takeover of its tiny neighbor 
he has stayed in the forefront of the antiiraq resistance 
alliances were reshaped where necessary he scrapped a political 
and economic grouping with iraq jordan and yemen he downgraded 
relations markedly with the palestine liberation organization 
mubarak said recently that egyptian soldiers would not enter 
iraq even if bush sent in us troops against saddam and asked 
mubarak to follow with peacekeeping forces as the americans 
withdrew 
but the egyptian leaders comment was merely a restatement of 
his policy since he sent the first of 14000 egyptians in 
midaugust to defend saudi arabia from possible iraqi attack 
arab politics being what they are it was a clever move said 
political science professor earl sullivan of american university in 
cairo it cost him nothing as long as his troop stay on the front 
line in saudi arabia and it ensured that saddam could not proclaim 
to the arabs that their brother mubarak was a traitor to the arab 
cause 
in terms of domestic politics hes more respected in a 
stronger position to lead the country internationally he looks 
like a statesman and a leader not a follower said sullivan who 
has followed middle eastern politics since coming to the university 
in 1973 
lucius d battle us ambassador to cairo during the 1960s 
praised mubarak for holding the course despite billions of dollars 
the crisis has cost egypts strapped economy 
the experience has not been all negative the united states has 
shown its appreciation by writing off almost 7 billion in military 
debts saudi arabia and other gulf arabs forgave another 7 
billion and cairo is expecting a receptive ear next week in paris 
when it asks further debt relief from mainly western creditor 
nations that would put egypts foreign debt at half the crippling 
50 billion it was on aug 1 
despite that said battle egypts economy has suffered a net 
loss since the turmoil began 
battle retired director of washingtons middle east institute 
said mubarak has performed extraordinarily well in difficult 
circumstances 
he has a real need for a relationship with united states 
partly economic and partly political battle said from his home 
in washington 
at the same time he said egypt cannot surrender leadership of 
the arabs to saddam or anybody else 
i think he has had economic incentive yes and political 
incentive to exert himself in the arab world in a leadership role 
i think thats in their interest and i think its in our 
interest said battle 
a muchneeded requirement for us is stability in that area 
mubarak is sensible hes moderate as steady and as sturdy as 
were likely to get there he said 
</TEXT>
