<TEXT>
two years ago lech walesa and tadeusz 
mazowiecki were sharing strikers rations and walking arminarm to 
topple communist rule they won the war but lost each other 
on sunday 27 million voters in polands first popular 
presidential election will write the final chapter to eastern 
europes most celebrated political divorce deciding which of them 
will hold the nations highest office 
the polls say walesa is far ahead the strongwilled solidarity 
chairman who inspires some and frightens others is striving to cap 
his amazing biography by succeeding his former communist nemesis 
gen wojciech jaruzelski as president 
mazowiecki the cautious and equally stubborn prime minister is 
opposing him 
and now a dark horse has emerged a wealthy mysteryshrouded 
emigre businessman stanislaw tyminski has returned after 21 years 
in canada and peru his fresh face freespending campaign and 
sharp attacks on familiar leaders have garnered him enough support 
to overtake mazowiecki in at least one preelection survey 
three remaining candidates excommunist wlodzimierz 
cimoszewski peasant party hopeful roman bartoszcze and leszek 
moczulski of the rightist confederation for an independent poland 
have failed to generate significant backing 
if nobody wins a majority the contest goes to a runoff dec 9 
the president will be sworn in before the national assembly by 
christmas the election is the first in eastern europe in which the 
electorate is not voting primarily against the former communist 
system rather it is choosing between differing visions of the new 
democratic system 
walesa the technicalschool educated electrician who has led 
solidarity from its birth in 1980 and won the 1983 nobel peace 
prize for his defense of workers rights is dynamic and volatile 
his opponents say he could become a dictator or at least 
destabilize the country 
mazowiecki is a catholic journalist and expolitical prisoner 
who in august 1989 with walesas backing became east europes first 
noncommunist head of government his opponents say he is reluctant 
to take action and will not move fast enough to satisfy public 
moods risking a social explosion 
walesa and mazowiecki were allies until the dissolution of their 
former common opponent the communist party in january over the 
next few months walesa began agitating from gdansk to replace the 
president and the 65 percent of the lower parliament chamber that 
has been conceded to the communists in a powersharing bargain by 
solidarity last year 
adopting the slogan of acceleration he also demanded 
quicker privatization of the 80 percent of the economy owned by the 
state removal of the old communist elite from powerful positions 
and speedy withdrawal of the soviet army 
mazowiecki responded that he shared the same goals but that 
everything must be accomplished gradually through the building of a 
state of law mazowieckis supporters in warsaw accused walesa of 
acting out of personal ambition and suggested he leave the running 
of poland to experts 
by the summer walesa had openly declared war at the top 
his backers and mazowieckis began forming new parties solidarity 
effectively split up 
workers and farmers tended to stay with their bluecollar 
champion walesa and the solidarity union itself has been a 
powerful engine in his energetic presidential campaign 
government officials professionals the more educated and more 
affluent including nearly all of walesas former intellectual 
advisers sided with mazowiecki 
behind the bitter personal conflict are differing concepts of 
democratic leadership in a country where the term after a half 
century of nazi or communist rule is still hazy 
walesa says poland needs a leader with an ax ready and 
determined to chop out vestiges of the old system and intervene 
when he sees injustice he says he can be a powerful cheerleader 
for change 
but mazowiecki says he fears such a charismatic leader 
accountable to no one he wants the president to be a guarantor 
of stability 
also at stake is the governments yearlong shock economic reform 
program that has restored stability to the polish market and 
quenched hyperinflation 
but the plan also cut poles real income by 35 percent brought 
on a deep recession and created 1 million unemployed 
walesa says he supports the tough plan and its architect deputy 
prime minister leszek balcerowicz who might even be offered the 
premiership if the solidarity chief wins however walesa wants 
faster privatization and more government support to give private 
enterprise a jump start 
mazowiecki responds that his privatization timetable is the 
fastest possible for selling half 7000 state enterprises within 
three years 
he says the election of walesa could upset poland as it is 
rounding a dangerous curve threatening all the hardwon domestic 
and international achievements of the past year and slowing down 
the countrys integration with the rest of europe 
if defeated mazowiecki says he will resign as prime minister 
and move into political opposition 
walesa has said if defeated he will quit as solidarity chairman 
and retire until the polish nation needs him again but he does not 
expect to lose 
i was born only for victory he declared in an interview 
</TEXT>
