<TEXT>
the centers for disease control announced a new 
program friday that the agency hopes will help doctors hear about 
outbreaks of potentially fatal respiratory viruses sooner 
the cdc is monitoring respiratory syncytial rsv and 
parainfluenza viruses which cause a variety of often serious 
respiratory ailments especially in young children 
previously health officials had alerted the cdc of outbreaks by 
weekly postcards now they will report the viruses by telephone 
enabling the cdc to post the results on the national public health 
network weekly 
cdc epidemiologist james alexander said the timeliness will help 
doctors and public health officials hear of outbreaks sooner thus 
cutting down on the number of diagnostic tests ill children undergo 
and possibly helping doctors prevent spread of the virus 
the study shows that rsv is most often found in january rsv 
causes kinds of bronchial illnesses that can be fatal to infants or 
sickly children and it hits almost every child by age 2 
the cdc found that the two least serious types of parainfluenza 
known as types 1 and 2 and which cause colds and croup usually 
cause outbreaks every other fall especially in november 
parainfluenza type 3 is more serious and causes types of 
bronchitis and pneumonia in infants and the elderly which can be 
fatal it is found yearround but the cdc study indicates it peaks 
in spring 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

