<TEXT>
opposition parties in serbia said 
friday they will boycott the republics first free elections in 50 
years because ruling officials rejected demands to change rules on 
casting and counting ballots 
the republics communistcontrolled parliament on thursday 
denied requests to allow opposition officials into staterun 
ballotcounting commissions and permit some serbs abroad to vote 
in the dec 9 election 
a statement by 12 opposition parties said parliaments decision 
blocked the most elementary conditions for fair elections and 
wiped out the last chance of compromise with the ruling 
socialists the new name adopted by the communist party 
the statement also demanded the resignation of serbias 
communist president slobodan milosevic and the ouster of parliament 
leaders and other communist officials 
the parties urged voters to join the boycott and attend a 
protest rally dec 3 in belgrade 
the statement was signed by leaders of the centerright serbian 
renewal movement the democratic party the serbian branch of 
federal premier ante markovics alliance of reformist forces and 
other parties 
about 50 opposition parties are registered for the vote many 
have complained they had less access to statecontrolled media for 
their campaigns 
vuk draskovic who was the top challenger to milosevic said his 
renewal movement had planned to contest all 250 parliament seats 
but under the boycott only milosevics socialists and a few newly 
formed communist groups would run he said 
the statement said unfair elections would make serbia along 
with albania the last bolshevik ghetto in europe and isolate the 
republic 
following the vote thursday parliament chairman zoran sokolovic 
said current law drawn up by the socialists ensures democratic 
elections 
nebojsa popov head of the small opposition union for yugoslav 
democratic initiative said the vote would be a farce under the 
present election rules 
serbia the largest of yugoslavias six republics and 
montengro the smallest are the last to hold multiparty elections 
communists were ousted last spring in the western republics of 
slovenia and croatia 
in the central state of bosniahercegovina nationalist parties 
had a landslide victory over communists 
in last novembers singleparty serbian elections unregistered 
voters were allowed to cast ballots in some districts milosevic 
