immigrant herbert bondy who was 16 when his family fled austria 
in 1938 after germany occupied the country 
bondy who retired in 1980 had been received social security 
payments as well as benefits for the blind when he received his 
first reparation payment from austria in 1988 the social security 
administration counted the payments as income and disqualified him 
from benefits for his blindness 
henderson ruled that reparations from austria must be treated 
like those from germany referring to a 1984 ruling by the 9th us 
circuit court of appeals that excluded german reparations as income 
in determining eligibility for federal benefits 
about 8800 people in the united states receive austrian 
reparations an estimated 158 to 572 also collect federal benefits 
for the aged blind or disabled henderson said 
the us government has argued that only those interned by the 
nazis qualified for reparations 
henderson quoted the austrian consul general in los angeles as 
explaining austrian reparations were for a moral obligation in 
view of the great injustice and heavy suffering inflicted on the 
victims of nazi persecution while austria was under nazi 
occupation 
austria won back its independence in 1945 at the end of world 
war ii 
according to the national jewish congress austria had 
antijewish laws as early as 1935 and in 1938 jews commonly 
suffered beatings lootings and deportations a lawyer for the 
group j mark waxman described the reparations as modest but said 
he didnt know precise amounts 
the governments attorney could not be reached for comment 
friday 
</TEXT>
