life in which things were bad is being released in a moment in 
which things couldnt be better 
everything has gone so well said the grinning babyfaced 
director his eyes sparkling behind hornrimmed glasses im 
sorry there was so much delay 
two years after its dismal debut cinema paradiso is alive 
and well in italian cinemas and has drawn crowds in europe japan 
and the united states 
now the question is whether tornatore can succeed again and 
prove himself an heir to federico fellini bernardo bertolucci and 
other great italian directors 
his new film stanno tutti bene theyre all fine produced 
by angelo rizzoli has just been released in italy and is due to 
open in the united states in february 
it tells of an elderly mans journey through italy to visit his 
five widely scattered children whom he wants to reunite for a 
dinner 
the father played by marcello mastroianni is chagrined to 
discover that his children have drifted from him and have hidden 
their failures at work and in marriage 
i wanted to make a film about the difficulty there is today in 
personal communication said tornatore sipping mineral water in 
a cafe near his apartment by the vatican wall 
we live in an era of communication of mass media but the 
nearer we move to events the more difficult it is to communicate 
with people 
while the film displays tornatores keen eye for the italian 
character and for daytoday human comedy it is more melancholy 
than cinema paradiso a semiautobiographical tale of a child 
enraptured by the silver screen 
stanno tutti bene was written in a moment of my life in 
which things were bad i identified with the moods of people 
especially those who were suffering and also their failures 
tornatore said 
a movie buff who began making documentaries at age 20 tornatore 
already had two films to his credit la camorrista the 
camorra member and cinema paradiso 
but they made little money cinema paradiso a cherished 
personal project attracted little notice and quickly closed 
tornatore feared he would no longer be able to make his own films 
but then cinema paradiso won an award at the 1989 cannes 
film festival and returned to movie theaters it went on to become 
the first italian film to win best foreign film at the academy 
awards since fellinis amarcord in 1975 
i am happy because what happened was important he said he 
added however that now i dont have any more time not even 
to know if im fine or not 
the idea for theyre all fine came about four years ago when 
tornatore saw a dignified elderly man with a suitcase eating alone 
in a roman trattoria 
i thought to myself where is he going i invented the idea 
that he was searching for his kids 
the fathers personal saga has modern italy as its backdrop 
peopled by powerobsessed young professionals african immigrants 
sleeping in cardboard boxes and elderly parents closeted in 
retirement homes by their children 
tornatore who like the father comes from a sicilian town 
objects to an urban society that has allowed answering machines and 
television to eclipse human conservation 
i was conscious of the fact that during the day i call paris 
or tokyo or send faxes sometimes i make friendships by fax 
without ever seeing the persons face said tornatore then 
when i return home i dont know who lives next door the long 
distances have shrunk the small distances have become longer 
he said the films title sums up the gloss we use to cover the 
difficulties of modernday society 
its a phrase we say every day we are all always just too 
happy he said theres no one who says im not fine 
maybe its a world of hidden unhappiness maybe its easier to 
finish it there people prefer to say something uncomplicated 
its very symptomatic of this era 
</TEXT>
