<TEXT>
south africa faces economic 
problems that are intertwined with the blackwhite political 
conflict and may be as difficult to solve 
a yearold recession is expected to last through 1991 
unemployment is rising black shantytowns are expanding and whites 
are joining the lines at soup kitchens 
economics has become a major part of the debate on south 
africas future 
government officials and most other whites say capitalism is the 
quickest route to prosperity for all the african national congress 
and other antiapartheid groups particularly labor unions favor 
socialism and demand a major redistribution of the wealth 
controlled by whits 
the economic debate is likely to become a great deal more 
heated if south africa shifts to longterm stagflation said 
business day the countrys leading financial daily the merits 
of a market economy are less obvious when a stagnant economy is 
accompanied by ever rising prices south africas economy is the 
strongest and most diverse on an impoverished continent but is 
expected to shrink about 2 percent this year and not to grow in 
1991 
with the population increasing at more than 2 percent a year 
president fw de klerk says the economy needs at least 5 percent 
annual growth if living conditions for blacks are to improve 
substantially 
as the economy declines black expectations are rising with de 
klerks political reforms and his promise to dismantle the 
apartheid system of racial segregation 
blacks in south africa have long equated apartheid with 
capitalism and many expect a new political system to bring major 
economic changes for many blacks that means socialism despite its 
failure in eastern europe and elsewhere in africa 
annual per capita income for south african blacks is equivalent 
to more than 1000 making it one of africas highest figures but 
only a fraction of what the average south african white earns 
no accurate unemployment figures are available but private 
economists say the rate is at least 15 percent for blacks and that 
20 percent to 30 percent more are underemployed in the southern 
city of port elizabeth black unemployment is almost 50 percent 
operation hunger which feeds needy blacks in rural areas 
estimates it is helping 15 million people up from about 1 million 
at the start of 1990 
we are getting more requests for help than ever before said 
bernie cohen financial director of the 10yearold organization 
john rees who runs the methodist care food distribution project 
in johannesburg said growing numbers of whites are losing their 
jobs and seeking assistance 
de klerks government recently conceded that the black housing 
shortage a perennial crisis is getting worse as 1 million blacks 
a year move to cities in search of work about 7 million of the 
countrys 30 million blacks already live in shacks they built 
themselves private groups report 
the government speaks of spending more to improve black living 
conditions but supports a huge bureaucracy created by apartheid 
about one of every three working whites is employed by the 
government much of the bureaucracy is duplicated in a system that 
has separate branches for whites blacks asains and people of 
mixed race plus separate structures in the 10 black homelands 
strikes by black workers have increased as unions demand higher 
wages from white managements accustomed to cheap labor gold 
mining for example faces a combination of rapidly rising costs 
and a stagnant world price 
south africa is the worlds largest producer of gold which 
provides more than 40 percent of its export earnings but many of 
its mines are among the worlds deepest and most expensive to 
operate 
gold is hovering at about 380 an ounce on world markets the 
magazine financial mail said the industry will continue to 
battle as long as the price stays under 400 and this will 
ripple through the economy as recession deepens 
an estimated 31000 of the 500000 workers in gold mining have 
lost their jobs in the past year and about 15 mines are in 
financial trouble according to the chamber of mines an umbrella 
group of leading companies 
foreign economic sanctions imposed because of apartheid also 
have hurt but no one can say exactly how much 
sanctions have shut off loans from internatonal lending 
agencies and more than half of the 300 us companies that did 
business in south africa five years ago have left 
the anc the main black opposition group wants sanctions to 
continue as a way to keep pressure on the government but plans to 
review its policy in light of de klerks reforms and the worsening 
economy 
