<TEXT>
la asunta bolivia ap the coca boom is over and armando 
chavez is learning to grow something else 
chavez an aymara indian is one of thousands of farmers in this 
remote andean region who are making the transition to coffee 
fruit soybeans and other crops with the help of a un project 
he said the program is like a dream to us now we have 
advisers fertilizer and insecticies they have introduced 
soybeans built schools and roads if the project left the area we 
would be like orphans 
the un project is the cornerstone of a bolivian government 
effort to wean farmers away from coca the base of cocaine 
our purpose is to change the illicit economy created by the 
cocacocaine axis and enable farmers to diversify their crops 
oswaldo antezana undersecretary of the interior for alternative 
development said in an interview before farmers were 
antagonistic 
chavez 39 his wife and four children live in an adobe hut on a 
treecovered hill outside la asunta a town of dirt streets and 
more tinroofed adobe huts it is near the yungas a cocaproducing 
region in the subtropical andean foothills east of la paz 
a fourwheeldrive vehicle needs seven hours to cover the 150 
miles from la paz to la asunta the narrow road runs along sheer 
cliffs hundreds of feet above cascading rivers that feed the 
amazon 
farmers get from the road to fields across the chasms in 
makeshift conveyances suspended from cables many of them suffer 
from yellow fever or tuberculosis 
when the cocaine boom began in the late 1970s coca production 
spread from the yungas to la asunta 
migrants from the highlands and the yungas moved in cleared the 
forests and planted coca for sale to traffickers the area became a 
no mans land where outsiders particular police were not welcome 
chavez moved to la asunta 11 years ago hoping coca would 
improve his lot then coca prices started down two years ago and he 
decided to call it quits because there is a law requiring the 
reduction of coca and we cannot live only from coca 
when prices dropped below the cost of production it wasnt 
even worth harvesting the leaf he said 
prices were driven down in part because of the colombian 
governments crackdown on cocaine traffickers last year and 
increased interdiction activities in bolivia 
chavez heads one of the seven community development centers in 
la asunta that receive financial and technical support from the 
un project his center is introducing the raising of pigs and 
fish and the cultivation of coffee soybeans spices and fruit 
veterinarians agronomists and health workers assist farmers 
through the centers 
jairo morales nieto chief tecnical adviser on the un project 
said the centers are involved in product development production 
and marketing as well as in training the farmers 
in contrast to many other rural areas in latin america in 
bolivia there is a remarkably organized peasant social base and 
peasant organizations have worked effectively for their members 
interests he said 
farmers get a credit of 2000 for every hectare about 2 
acres of coca they destroy loans seeds and fertilizer are 
provided as farmers progress in planting new crops and raising 
animals 
because one of the main problems in remote regions has been 
getting products to market the un project has financed new 
roads 
two years ago it took eight hours in good weather to travel 
between la asunta and chulumani a market town about 70 miles to 
the south and longer in the rain now it takes three hours 
the un fund for drug abuse control has spent 21 million on 
the project which has helped 150000 farmers since it began in 
1985 the money runs out this year but the government hopes for an 
extension 
as long as coca cultivation increases in the region there is 
a greater possibility of cocaine traffickers and violence moving 
in said arturo villanueva an adviser who showed visitors 
experimental shrimp tanks financed by the project 
an estimated 125000 acres are devoted to coca cultivation in 
bolivia the government hopes to cut that to about 30000 which is 
considered sufficient for the leafs traditional applications 
coca is used as a medicine in religious rituals as a tea and 
is chewed by farmers and miners to help counteract the effects of 
high altitude and hunger 
twothirds of bolivian coca is grown in the chapare a flat 
tropical region east of la asunta both the united nations and 
united states are financing alternative development programs there 
but with less success than in la asunta 
bolivian farmers have destroyed a record 20 percent of the 
countrys coca crop since october 1989 
we have learned to establish a clear distinction between the 
peasants and the drug dealers said morales nieto the un 
technical adviser generally the peasants want to abide by the 
law 
