<TEXT>
by the time the current economic downturn runs 
its course some wall street analysts contend it could shake up 
the way many people think about american investments 
for example they suggest just suppose that recession and a 
change in attitudes toward the use of credit bring about a 
longlasting decline in interest rates 
bonds might lose their modern image as volatile securities and 
return to something at least a little like the slowandstodgy days 
of yore 
real estate even with lower mortgage interest rates might 
emerge lacking some of the luster it acquired over the past two 
decades as a prime beneficiary of an inflationdriven economy 
moneymarket mutual funds treasury bills and other shortterm 
interestbearing investments could also fade from their present 
exalted status as their yields declined 
as for stocks well just possibly they could flourish 
provided the business world was able to find and develop important 
new sources of growth 
of course all this is conjecture akin to a longrange weather 
forecast based on a series of assumptions and interpretations that 
have not yet been tested by the course of realworld events 
the prospect of a sustained drop in interest rates by itself is 
far from an accepted idea 
still visions of this sort serve at least one present purpose 
challenging any presumptions that the nation is simply going 
through a down cycle that will reliably give way sooner or later to 
a return of businessasbefore on wall street 
we argue that todays recession will complete the job that 
began at the outset of the 1980s says robert j barbera 
economist at shearson lehman brothers inc in a current appraisal 
of the outlook 
inflation collapsed after the economic downturns early in the 
decade but inflation psychology lingered debt usage a bet that 
inflation would return thrived despite low inflation 
high real shortterm interest rates were necessary to contain 
us economic growth in a debtaddicted society today however 
both borrowers and lenders are much more circumspect about the use 
of debt 
signs of at least a shortterm drop in rates have lifted 
investors spirits of late although that mood of optimism seemed 
to be on hold in the past week 
the dow jones average of 30 industrials closed friday at 
252723 down 2302 points from the week before 
the new york stock exchange composite index slipped 91 to 
17239 the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter market 
dropped 181 to 34904 and the american stock exchange market 
