<TEXT>
while the demise of junk bond financier michael 
milken symbolizes an era gone sour his cooperation with 
prosecutors could lead to another round of highprofile wall street 
cases lawyers said 
us district judge kimba wood who sentenced milken to an 
unexpectedly harsh 10 years in prison and three years probation 
held open the possibility of reducing the term to reward 
cooperation 
milken associates said thursday that the exhead of junk bond 
trading at drexel burnham lambert inc whose ideas about debt 
reshaped us corporate finance in the 1980s was devastated by the 
sentence 
milken 44 and his wife lori returned to their home in the 
encino suburb of los angeles shortly after the sentencing wednesday 
in manhattan federal court they were said to be spending 
thanksgiving at home with their three children aged 17 14 and 9 
defense lawyers for milkn subordinates at drexel said they 
believed the judge gave a stiff term partly to send a message about 
the value of helping the government 
she is communicating clearly to michael and his attorneys that 
if she is going to entertain the possibility of reducing sentence 
he must completely and totally cooperate said aubrey harwell 
jr who represented a former drexel trader who received immunity 
from prosecution and testified against milken 
the sentence if no reduction occurs effectively means milken 
will spend a minimum of nearly seven years in jail and on 
probation denying him complete freedom until at least sometime in 
1998 
in a deal pleading guilty to six felony counts milken agreed to 
respond truthfully to any questions posed by the government after 
sentencing 
lawyers involved in the case said they expected prosecutors to 
target corporate officials who dealt with milken 
one of the topics of conversation in the last 24 hours is that 
if michael completely and totally cooperates and provides 
information on corporate chieftains connected to his work this 
sentence will be significantly reduced said one defense lawyer 
who asked not to be named 
the lawyer said he believe the government would start out by 
gently pushing him push him harder and harder and bring more 
pressure to bear 
milkens sentence is far stricter than any previous in wall 
streets corruption scandals which evolved largely from 
information supplied by speculator ivan boesky who received a 
threeyear prison term after settling insider trading charges 
dennis levine a former drexel investment banker got two years 
after agreeing to return 126 million in illegal gains from 
trading on inside information mergers specialist martin siegel 
who accepted suitcases of cash in exchange for inside information 
spent two months in prison 
the main difference between those cases and milkens legal 
experts agreed is the three cooperated before sentencing which 
judges consider a mitigating factor and milken didnt 
judge wood said in a subtle way that boesky cooperated and 
you didnt how can you expect to get a sentence thats equal to 
his said harry first a law professor at new york university 
milken was involved in thousands of financings mergers and 
other transactions and the government is known to have been 
scrutinizing several deals first said milken and his attorneys now 
must decide how much to help prosecutors 
martin klein a new york lawyer and friend of milkens called 
woods offer of a sentence reduction in return for good cooperation 
coercive 
that assumes that he has anything to say klein said this 
whole idea of getting people to turn on others sets a bad precedent 
in this country 
milken must report to federal custody next march no prison was 
designated but under federal guidelines milken initially could not 
go to a minimumsecurity camp because of the length of his term 
legal experts said he likely will be eligible for parole upon 
serving onethird of his term during probation wood required 
1800 hours of community service a year or 346 hours a week 
milkens lawyers have 120 days to appeal the sentence through a 
motion seeking reduction a milken spokesman would not say whether 
a decision had been made milken had faced a maximum 28 years 
since milkens crimes occurred before 1987 his sentencing was 
not based on federal guidelines that specify punishment but two 
factors cited by the judge meriting a longer sentence under the 
guidelines were milkens position of authority and the commission 
of crimes she said were hard to detect 
wood told the court anothr component of her decision was 
milkens behavior after boeskys november 1986 plea deal with 
authorities 
she said milken didnt directly order subordinates to destroy or 
remove documents but communicated the advisability of their doing 
so in subtle terms that preserved some deniability on your part 
wood said she did not accept government charges at a 
presentencing hearing last month that milken committed insider 
trading or manipulated a particular stock that made the long 
prison term more shocking to associates 
she found for us on those issues said a friend of milkens 
who asked not to be named if she found against us what would she 
have done twentyeight years 
