<TEXT>
the hong kong government on friday revised the 
forecast for this british colonys gross domestic product in 1990 
to 23 percent from 25 percent predicted in august 
it also revised the inflation rate to 97 percent from 95 
percent 
the government chief economist k y tang said the colonys 
economy could have been harder hit by the slowdown in domestic 
exports to the united states britain and japan if not for 
continued strong growth in reexports 
a government statement said domestic exports in the third 
quarter continued to decline by about 2 percent in real terms over 
a year earlier while imports rose about 12 percent in the same 
period 
however reexports goods assembled in hong kong of components 
made elsewhere increased by about 14 percent in the third quarter 
over the same period in 1989 the statement said 
</TEXT>
