<DOCNO> AP901123-0158 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
eleven staterun coal mines will 
be closed over the next two years under efforts to streamline 
moneylosing industries the government says 
economics minister vladimir dlouhy said thursday that about 
9500 workers will be laid off at the mines located mostly in the 
ostrava region about 240 miles east of prague 
dlouhy said the mines are unprofitable but have been kept open 
to supply coalfired electric power stations 
two major power stations and several smaller generators face 
shutdown over the same twoyear period to reduce pollution dlouhy 
said 
the 750megawatt power shortfall resulting from the closures 
would be covered by an expanding nuclear power program he said 
czechoslovakia already has two sovietdesigned nuclear plants in 
operation and two under construction 
a 440megawatt reactor at the new mohovce station is scheduled 
to start up in 1991 and a 1000megawatt installation is slated to 
begin operating in 1992 at temelin a new plant near the austrian 
border 
workers from the closed power stations will be relocated or 
retrained dlouhy said 
miners in north moravia have been on strike alert all week 
demanding better social conditions for themselves and their 
families 
dlouhy said the mines and power stations would not be 
dismantled and could be reopened quickly if needed 
czechoslovakia and other east european nations are bracing for a 
harsh winter because of reduced soviet oil imports and higher crude 
oil prices following the persian gulf crisis 
regular annual imports of 16 million tons of soviet oil are 
expected to drop to 12 million tons next year 
</TEXT>
