<DOCNO> AP901123-0167 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal reserve has allowed shortterm 
interest rates to fall moderately but tight lending practices and 
depressed bank earnings could delay the moves effect on the 
economy 
normally lower shortterm interest rates take about a month to 
show up in a lower prime rate lower adjustable rate mortgages and 
cheaper car loans economists said it might take another year to 
18 months for lending activity to increase as more consumers decide 
to buy new houses and cars 
but interest rates are only one element of credit 
availability theres a credit crunch and homebuilders are having 
trouble getting financing said bob villanueva chief economist 
at the national association of home builders 
the federal reserve this past week confirmed what many borrowers 
already knew banks under pressure from regulators have become 
reluctant to make loans their caution has been chiefly aimed at 
commercial real estate borrowers but has also affected typically 
safe large corporations and home buyers 
bankers and business owners complain that regulators are 
overreacting to the savings and loan debacle and discouraging banks 
from making reasonable loans 
the bush administration wants lower interest rates to mean 
easier credit 
treasury secretary nicholas brady this past week urged bank 
examiners not to discourage banks from making loans 
also an interest rate cut could move through the economy more 
slowly if banks try to bolster their weak earnings by delaying a 
cut in the prime rate and absorbing the lower federal funds rate 
the lower fed funds rate without a corresponding cut in the prime 
increases the spread between the price banks pay for money and what 
they charge to lend it 
another source of money for banks certificates of deposit have 
yet to come down much 
moreover some doubt the fed has allowed shortterm rates to 
fall enough and say it should move more aggressively to 
significantly strengthen the economy 
the economy which is certainly very sluggish right now is 
not going to burst out of the shoot because the fed allowed the fed 
funds rate to come down 25 hundredths of a percentage point in the 
past few days said ken goldstein an economist at the conference 
board 
in 25 basispoint increments the fed has lowered the federal 
funds rate the interest banks charge each other for overnight 
loans twice in recent months from 8 percent to 7 percent 
if the 50 basis point drop in the federal funds rate is 
translated into a half percentage point drop in the prime rate the 
effects could trickle into consumer loans within weeks goldstein 
said 
but for businesses to spring back to life and lead a resurgence 
in economic growth is just whistling in the dark he said 
if the lower interest rates find their way to a lower prime rate 
and is accompanied by easier lending practices by banks a half 
percentage point cut could lead to about 40000 new housing units 
in a quarter villanueva said 
but a more meaningful and aggressive move to lower rates rather 
than allowing them to fall would be difficult for the fed 
the dollar already has weakened severely on world currency 
markets and if us interest rates fall further without 
corresponding drops in japan and germany the dollar would weaken 
more 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
