<DOCNO> AP901123-0169 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
with not much else to cheer about in the 
economic news wall street has grown much more optimistic in recent 
weeks about the inflation outlook 
in the forefront of the financial news oil prices have fallen 
of late from the peaks they reached after iraqs aug 2 invasion of 
kuwait but beyond that analysts see other trends they describe as 
even more heartening 
some broad indexes of industrial commodity prices actually 
reached their peaks for the year before the oil upsurge 
in recent weeks these gauges of inflationary pressures have 
declined steadily to their lowest levels since late last winter 
the inflation picture is becoming less worrisome said jack 
lavery director of global research at merrill lynch amp co energy 
price increases are abating and are not spreading elsewhere the 
economy is too weak 
amid this kind of encouragement anxious talk about 
stagflation has died down in the financial world 
a few months ago concern was rising that the economy was headed 
for a spell of double trouble little or no growth combined with 
persistent upward pressure on the cost of living 
operating under that script the federal reserve would have 
hardly any maneuvering room to try to counter either problem since 
a stimulative policy to counteract recession would only make 
inflation worse while a militant antiinflation stand would deepen 
the economic slump 
now that perceived dilemma seems to have been resolved most 
analysts agree that ebbing inflation has made it possible for the 
fed to adopt a less stringent approach in managing the supply of 
money and credit in the economy 
the shift has been cautious and gradual reflecting a style that 
has become familiar to fedwatchers under the chairmanship of alan 
greenspan 
the central bank has made no move as yet to change the discount 
rate which has stood at 7 percent since it was raised to that 
level on feb 24 1989 in the past the fed has often used changes 
in the discount rate the charge it sets on loans to private 
financial institutions to signal important monetarypolicy moves 
in many analysts view greenspan has been sticking with a 
deliberate style in an effort to gain and keep the confidence of 
bond traders that he wont let his guard down on inflation 
the letup in inflation fears has helped to ease what some 
observers view as a simplistic initial reaction to the sharp rise 
in oil prices 
even if we knew for sure at what level oil prices will settle 
the consequences are not as predictable as might be imagined 
said economists at hc wainwright amp co of boston in a recent 
report on the subject 
inflation is a monetary phenomenon they argue no single 
commodity can drive the prices of all commodities up only the 
federal government by depreciating the value of the currency can 
do that 
indeed an energy price increase works the other way by 
absorbing a larger slice of the incomes of energy users it makes 
the existing prices of other commodities less affordable 
if however government intervenes to ratify or monetize 
an oil price increase then inflation will result 
</TEXT>
