<TEXT>
about 500 miners in hardhats and coveralls 
staged a noisy 90minute demonstration in front of parliament 
friday demanding increased government subsidies for financially 
troubled coal mines 
a petition handed to the lower parliament house said a cut in 
subsidies under the governments radical economic reforms has made 
the mines unprofitable and cut the miners living standards the 
state pap news agency reported 
the demonstrators also demanded talks with the government on 
wages pap said 
miners in a series of recent warning strikes have demanded 
twice the national average of 12 million zlotys or 130 a month 
in base pay 
traditionally in poland miners commanded much higher wages than 
other workers because of the importance of their industry and the 
difficult dangerous working conditions 
but polands postcommunist government wants to transform mining 
into a profitmaking industry and huge government subsidies are 
being cut back slowly while coal prices are allowed to rise 
many of the miners demonstrating were from the communistfounded 
opzz trade union federation leaders met with mieczyslaw gil head 
of the solidarityallied citizens parliamentary caucus senate 
speaker andrzej stelmachowski and various deputies 
fridays protest came only two days before the countrys first 
popular presidential election i dont think its an accident 
gil said on state television 
rajmund moric head of the opzz mining union said 
representatives of parliament and the government would visit the 
mining region of silesia on dec 1 
a 31yearold miner ryszard chojnowski collapsed during the 
demonstration and later died pap reported the cause of death was 
being investigated the agency said 
