<DOCNO> AP901123-0192 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
about two years ago michael milken had a chance 
to plead guilty to a couple felony counts and end the governments 
investigation before a single charge had ever been brought against 
him he didnt 
milken could have fought his case at trial bearing the pressure 
of lengthy public scrutiny but squarely confronting the 
governments claims which he and his defense lawyers maintained 
were spurious he didnt 
the 44yearold former drexel burnham lambert inc financier 
also could have spilled his guts long ago naming names and winning 
credit to earn a shorter sentence he didnt do that either 
now critics are gloating that the junk bond whiz got his 10 
years in prison and three years of fulltime community service 
just as watergate closed out the 1970s milkens punishment is 
viewed as a headstone for the 1980s the end of an era of greed 
but while no one predicted the severity of the sentence handed 
down last week by us district judge kimba wood legal experts are 
questioning milkens strategy during his fouryear confrontation 
with the justice department 
the lawyer has to follow the clients instructions said 
john j coffee jr a columbia university law professor milken 
was not some wimp who was totally dependent on his lawyers advice 
he knows his own personal calculus 
i think he probably estimated he might have served two or 
three years coffee said certainly no one predicted this as 
the likely outcome but a man who lives with junk bonds knows there 
are risks out there 
the general postmortem in the legal community is that milken 
and his highpriced defense team led by arthur liman may have 
miscalculated at various points among them 
balking at a deal with prosecutors about two years ago that 
would have allowed milken to plead guilty to two or three felony 
counts milken sources contend the government wanted an admission 
of insider trading which milken found unacceptable 
loudly criticizing the governments investigation indictment 
and tactics and trumpeting milkens innocence after the plea 
deal liman argued strenuously that milken was guilty only of 
technical violations in the end milken appeared to get little if 
any credit for settling the case 
pleading guilty to six felony counts an unheard of 
amount coffee said liman may have wrongly assumed the judge 
would discount the number of counts if she found they were minor 
breaches but wood sentenced milken to consecutive twoyear terms 
on each of five counts on count six conspiracy he got probation 
letting the government raise additional charges before 
sentencing when the defense contested the claims and wood couldnt 
square the pictures she held a hearing the judge didnt find 
milken had committed the substantive charges but she did find he 
obstructed justice during the federal probe a serious violation in 
judges eyes 
delaying cooperation until after sentencing wood toughened the 
sentence because milken had not assisted the government milken 
long had refused to cooperate now he faces a catch22 he has to 
snitch to qualify for a reduction but if his genuine assistance 
proves of little value he gets no credit 
milkens strategy did yield a few benefits he avoided the 
humiliation of a long trial that would have kept him and his family 
in the public eye for years and the government agreed to drop all 
charges against his brother lowell 
but several defense lawyers and legal scholars agreed that 
milkens approach during the fouryear ordeal was indecisive 
if youre going to rattle sabers youre better off going 
through with it said an attorney with a client involved in the 
milken case who asked not to be named if youre going to go in 
and try to cooperate you do it in a quiet meek way if youre 
going to grovel you grovel 
milken did none of those 
you cant cooperate halfway securities lawyer ira sorkin 
said either you go 100 percent or zero by saying youre really 
sorry feel terrible you hurt people but not telling the 
government more she perceived that as noncooperation 
in fairness to milken the secondguessing is pinned to the 
lengthy term which no one had anticipated 
there are all sorts of factors that went into that decision to 
plead guilty that we will never know about criminal defense 
lawyer judd burstein said you just cant look and say he made a 
bad decision because he got 10 years 
under his plea agreement milken now must answer any questions 
posed by the government judge wood said she would consider 
reducing the sentence based on a recommendation from the government 
praising milkens cooperation 
under federal law the defense has 120 days to request a 
reduction in sentence the us attorneys office would have to 
support the request if milken were to have any chance for a quick 
reduction 
before the government agrees to spring milken early he likely 
would have to provide information leading to other indictments a 
main focus is expected to be fraud in the collapse of the nations 
savings and loans which bought about 10 billion in risky 
highyield bonds from drexel 
bringing other types of cases is expected to be more difficult 
because federal law bars prosecution for crimes committed more than 
five years ago and many of the deals milken already are older than 
that congress last year extended the statute of limitations for 
sampls to 10 years 
while 120 days isnt much time milken could file the motion to 
reduce sentence and judge wood could delay it for months while he 
cooperates but that still might not be long enough to develop 
enough cases to satisfy prosecutors 
milkens next choice is how much to cooperate 
it sounds to me like shes laying out the red carpet for 
him said alan bromberg a securities law professor at southern 
methodist university how far down it he can go and how much good 
it will do is very hard to predict 
all ive heard is hes not a tattletale type it will go 
against the grain for him bromberg said 
michael is a basically loyal human being said a defense 
lawyer for a former drexel trader who testified against milken 
he has been very opposed to telling anything in regard to those 
people with whom he has dealt 
whatever milkens cooperation produces his sentence seemed to 
satisfy those who viewed milken as the embodiment of wall street 
greed despite a modest generous lifestyle that contrasted with 
that of his main accuser inside trader ivan boesky 
the handful of letters sent to the judge by people who dont 
know milken suggested life in prison or physical torture liman 
said the requests would probably stagger the secret police of 
totalitarian regimes the anger toward milken was great but many 
people on wall street said it was misdirected 
he was this eras target one defense lawyer said we are 
a society that likes to blame someone 
said sorkin the only conclusion that can be drawn is that 
there was greed before the 1980s and there will be greed after the 
1980s if you look at what the stock market was like in the first 
40 years of this century what boesky and milken and the rest of 
them did would pale by comparison 
</TEXT>
