<TEXT>
each day it seems theres an announcement about the soviet 
union reaching agreement for food aid with another western nation 
meanwhile the us farm sector watches these multibillion 
dollar deals from outside its nose pressed to the window 
yet hope persists despite repeated disappointments 
the european community cant provide soy oil and meal and 
the united states is about the only source for these commodities 
now said joel karlin a grain analyst in chicago with research 
department inc 
wheat can be bought cheaply enough from canada or argentina and 
barley can be substituted for corn if the united states is cut out 
of any extraordinary deals this fall with the soviets 
in the past month soviet leader mikhail gorbachev has arranged 
for 10 billion in emergency food aid to help his country get 
through the winter as these deals were announced corn and wheat 
traders at the chicago board of trade became more resigned to the 
belief that there wont be much if anything left over for us 
exporters of these commodities 
the bush administration has indicated that it is looking for 
liberalized emigration laws in the soviet union before its willing 
to talk export credits 
futures traders and grain analysts say they think bush will be 
more willing to help if gorbachev is firmly lined up with the us 
in dealing with iraq 
this line of reasoning sent soybean prices sharply higher a week 
ago before the meetings in europe between bush and gorbachev the 
gains were quickly lost when no grain deal was announced but 
quickly went back up again when gorbachev said the issue of force 
should be decided by the un security council 
by weeks end prices were back up on reports that the soviets 
were about to codify liberalized emigration laws further the 
market began talking about the arrival in washington on monday of a 
grainbuying team from the soviet union 
how much this team will focus on longterm trade arrangements 
and how much on immediate aid for this winter remains to be seen 
there seems to be a concensus in the market that eventually 
the soviets and the us will come to terms on emergency aid 
karlin said 
he noted that legislators and farm groups have become 
increasingly vocal on the need to give agricultural exports a shot 
in the arm 
us soy oil and meal presumably are on the soviet shopping 
list cooking oil is one among many food staples reported in 
critically short supply there and soybean oil is about the cheapest 
oil available and abundant supplies of soy meal make it the 
obvious choice for animal feed 
nonetheless said karlin if the soviets dont get credit they 
probably wont buy 
so if we dont so anything were going to be left behind 
he said 
here are some weekly commodity price trends 
soybean futures prices moved higher while the grains declined at 
the chicago board of trade 
wheat for delivery in december settled friday at 248 a 
bushel compared with 250 a week earlier december corn slipped 
to 222 a bushel from 225 december oats dropped to 108 a 
bushel from 111 and january soybeans moved to 582 a bushel 
from 578 
beef futures moved higher while pork declined at the chicago 
mercantile exchange 
live cattle for delivery in december settled at 7935 cents a 
pound compared with 7905 cents a week earlier january feeder 
cattle advanced to 8802 cents a pound from 8770 cents december 
hogs dropped to 5345 cents a pound from 5370 cents and frozen 
pork bellies for february delivery declined to 7140 cents a pound 
from 7212 cents 
gold moved higher while silver was essentially flat at the 
commodity exchange in new york 
december gold settled at 38450 a troy ounce up from 37980 
and silver dropped to 413 a troy ounce from 414 
petroleum futures prices moved higher at the new york mercantile 
exchange 
light sweet crude oil for delivery in january settled at 3190 
a barrel compared with 3064 december heating oil advanced to 
8866 cents a gallon from 8442 cents and heating oil settled at 
8240 cents a gallon up from 7763 cents 
